  "dateModified": "2026-03-06",
  "datePublished": "2026-03-06",
  "description": "Freewriting is a composing method in which the writer writes without stopping for a set period — without editing, pausing, rereading, or correcting. Peter Elbow introduced freewriting in Writing Without Teachers (1973) as a way to bypass the internal editor that blocks fluency [@elbow1973].\nThe point of freewriting isn\u0026rsquo;t to produce good prose. It\u0026rsquo;s to separate generation from evaluation — what Elbow later called first-order thinking (generative, associative, uncritical) from second-order thinking (analytical, editorial, critical). Most writers try to do both at once, which produces neither fluency nor quality [@elbow1981].\n",
  "name": "Freewriting",
